body: Does scenario 2 documented [here](https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/python/api_summary.html#iobinding) not work for you? You can fetch the torch data ptr using [this](https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.Tensor.data_ptr.html#torch.Tensor.data_ptr).

Thank you very much!
I'm afraid to admit that I wasn't aware of this documentation, and I tried to figure my way out from the tests.
I successfully passed a `torch` tensor allocated on CUDA gpu device directly to my ONNX model without copying it to the CPU - using `iobiding` and the tensor `data_ptr()` method.

PS. Creating an OrtValue from NumPy array (scenario 2 from the docs) works as expected. I didn't have issues with that.

issue.body:
Similar to #10217 

Can we run onnxruntime model with cupy array (with some conversions)?
I tried the **dlpack** way as mentioned in #4162 but I got module not found error with the statement `C.OrtValue.from_dlpack()`

Have I missed something or the installation is different as usual to support `from onnxruntime.capi import _pybind_state as C`?

I basically install onnxruntime as following:
```bash
# Ubuntu 18.04 with cuda 11.2
pip install onnxruntime-gpu==1.9.0
```

Thanks!

body: For future reference, it is also possible to create OrtValue from Torch tensor via dlpack. See  #10286 (note they mention the opposite direction but there is API for both conversion directions).

and much simpler (no need to recompile ORT) -> just provide the torch pointer to the output of your model, etc.:
```python
binding = session.io_binding()
...
# test export to Torch tensor directly
# https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/api/python/api_summary.html#iobinding
logit_output = torch.empty((2, 128, 50257), dtype=torch.float32, device='cuda')
binding.bind_output(name=onnx_named_outputs[0], device_type='cuda', device_id=0, element_type=np.float32, shape=tuple(logit_output.shape), buffer_ptr=logit_output.data_ptr())
```
Is there any way to initiate the torch tensor without specifying its shape (I need it for the inputs with dynamic shape)?

unlike TensorRT, ONNX Runtime has no way to infer output shape from input shape.
So it's up to the user to guess the output shape. In my case I have found that naming input and output axis in the same way to indicate that they should have the same size is a good solution, but i may not work for you.

Thanks a lot for your response.
Is it possible that we allocate the size to the maximum and our input size will be less than the maximum?

As I said, it is possible. See here:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/fdce4fa6af437b0b822958ab47b3b8f77f9e14ae/orttraining/orttraining/python/training/ortmodule/_utils.py#L50-L59
